Ordered the ramen, Spicy squid, Gogogi chicken, and the Soy garlic chicken wings to eat in. It's a small tight place owned and managed by a Korean family who are fast at prepping the food. Seems like most people order to-go here.  Ramen isn't as great as shin ramen but still totally hits the spot and is a godsend on any godforsaken winter day. Spicy squid is soft, not rubbery. Tastes okay. Gogogi chicken is okay. Mostly chicken breast, though it's hard to tell if it's fresh or the strips you get from fast Chinese food joints. While it's flavorful and crunchy, it can feel oily after a while and there are wide air bubbles/pockets under the battered skin of the chicken. The same is true for the wings. This isn't necessarily bad but noted. Good thing is the cilantro-mayo sauce that comes with the fried chicken. Cuts through the grease and is refreshing. The veggies that come with the gogogi chicken is oily and cold.  This isn't the place to go for the best but when it's the only one in the area, it is the best. Come here when you're craving Korean ramen or wings on a cold, dreary day.

While expensive, the bulgogi and bibimbap are solid choices, especially since this is the only place in the area for Korean food. Some of the lunch items can be made spicy (and they’re actually spicy!) There is very little sitting room, so call ahead and take things to go! There’s a $10 card minimum.
